WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
What is the role of a student of the Economic University?

00:05.000 --> 00:14.000
Good afternoon. Imagine that you are a student of the Economic University, who studied the basic economic and management disciplines for two years,

00:14.000 --> 00:19.000
the basics of macro and microeconomics, the basics of management, the basics of marketing, and so on.

00:19.000 --> 00:21.000
Well, in general, he met with the university students.

00:21.000 --> 00:28.000
Now he needs to choose a specialization for himself in order to become a cool professional in the field.

00:28.000 --> 00:34.000
It can be marketing, it can be logistics, it can be accounting, it can be controlling.

00:34.000 --> 00:39.000
And the student thinks about how to make this choice.

00:39.000 --> 00:47.000
He looks at the coin and thinks that, in principle, this choice can be made strategically by throwing the coin.

00:47.000 --> 00:53.000
If the coin falls to the floor and the eagle falls, then he can choose marketing for himself.

00:53.000 --> 00:57.000
If it falls to the top, then he will choose logistics for himself.

00:57.000 --> 01:01.000
If it hangs in the air, then it will be accounting.

01:01.000 --> 01:05.000
If the coin is on the edge, then it will be controlling.

01:05.000 --> 01:17.000
The second option is that he can look around, try to analyze what professions will be in demand in the market in the near future.

01:17.000 --> 01:27.000
And also look inside, close your eyes and think about what talents and inclinations I have, what attracts me the most.

01:27.000 --> 01:35.000
If this is a creative personality, then, of course, he will choose accounting for himself, remembering such a term as creative accounting.

01:36.000 --> 01:48.000
Companies, businesses often have the same situations when you understand that everything that has been so far cannot remain so and further.

01:48.000 --> 01:55.000
You need to live differently and you think where to go, to the right, to the left or straight.

01:56.000 --> 02:03.000
Companies often face the problem of a cardinal breakdown of the party's general line.

02:03.000 --> 02:08.000
And in order to do this consciously, they have to do a strategic analysis.

02:08.000 --> 02:12.000
Analysis of the external environment, analysis of oneself.

02:12.000 --> 02:21.000
We will discuss the key tools that can be used to make this analysis.

02:22.000 --> 02:27.000
My name is Vladislav Tolkach. I am the director of the Academy of Controlling.

02:27.000 --> 02:30.000
This is the main place of my work.

02:30.000 --> 02:38.000
This project is implemented by the joint efforts of the German School of Business and the Academy Controller.

02:38.000 --> 02:41.000
I am a practicing business coach and consultant.

02:41.000 --> 02:46.000
I specialize in the topic of strategy, organizational development and, of course, controlling.

02:46.000 --> 02:59.000
The main tools of strategic analysis that we will discuss are used to understand the environment of the external environment in which our company operates.

02:59.000 --> 03:05.000
There is a PEST analysis, or it is also called STEP.

03:05.000 --> 03:10.000
This is an abbreviation of four English words.

03:10.000 --> 03:16.000
This is an analysis of the political, economic, social and technological environment.

03:16.000 --> 03:20.000
If you make an abbreviation, it turns out either PEST or STEP.

03:20.000 --> 03:24.000
The second tool allows you to understand your industry.

03:24.000 --> 03:31.000
Here I must mention the work of the guru of strategic management, Michael Porter,

03:31.000 --> 03:39.000
who, for the sake of understanding his industry, recommends to businessmen to analyze competition, as well as the power of substitutes.

03:39.000 --> 03:51.000
These are products from adjacent industries that can gnaw money from the pie that we and our competitors in our industry claim.

03:51.000 --> 03:54.000
Here is the analysis of customers and suppliers.

03:54.000 --> 03:57.000
The fifth tool is the so-called entry barriers.

03:57.000 --> 04:01.000
This is what prevents potential players from breaking into our industry.

04:01.000 --> 04:07.000
The third tool is the analysis of the factors of success in the industry.

04:07.000 --> 04:12.000
In principle, it is a summary of the entire previous work.

04:12.000 --> 04:20.000
When we rewrite all the issues that should be solved in our industry, if we want to earn something,

04:20.000 --> 04:22.000
we need to work on them.

04:22.000 --> 04:24.000
However, these issues are usually divided into two parts.

04:24.000 --> 04:29.000
The first part is the basic issues that allow us to play football,

04:29.000 --> 04:33.000
allow us to play on the football field, but do not guarantee us a win.

04:33.000 --> 04:36.000
The second part is the so-called strategic issues.

04:36.000 --> 04:41.000
If we work strategically, we have a chance to win football.

04:41.000 --> 04:47.000
The fourth tool is the analysis of the strengths and weaknesses.

04:47.000 --> 04:52.000
This is the analysis of the company itself, what is good and what is not very good at the moment.

04:52.000 --> 04:59.000
The summary tool that summarizes the entire previous analytical work is the so-called SWOT analysis.

04:59.000 --> 05:01.000
This is again an English-language abbreviation.

05:01.000 --> 05:11.000
These four letters mean again the strengths and weaknesses, as well as the list of threats, opportunities and threats.

05:12.000 --> 05:17.000
The last part of our course is the organizational aspects.

05:17.000 --> 05:25.000
We will talk about how to do this analysis better, who to call to a strategic meeting, how to distribute roles.

05:25.000 --> 05:29.000
These are the nuances that we will discuss in the last part.

05:29.000 --> 05:36.000
In the 1970s, the Armenian radio was asked if a snake could break its spine.

05:36.000 --> 05:42.000
The Armenian radio thought and replied that a snake could break its spine if it crawled along the party's general line.

05:42.000 --> 05:48.000
Sometimes the company experiences a stage of a radical break in the party's general line,

05:48.000 --> 05:51.000
when the leadership comes to work on Monday and says,

05:51.000 --> 05:58.000
guys, everything is wrong, everything we do is wrong, it was right before, but it is not right in the future.

05:58.000 --> 06:05.000
We must remake our strategy, remake our business model, go another way, otherwise we will not survive.

06:05.000 --> 06:13.000
Imagine that you are a distributor of body care, home chemistry, cosmetics, and you are in a tight spot.

06:13.000 --> 06:21.000
On the one hand, the factory is pressuring you, twisting your hands at the price and payment conditions.

06:21.000 --> 06:27.000
On the other hand, the clients are pressing you harder, who also twist your hands at the price and payment conditions.

06:27.000 --> 06:32.000
In addition, the competition is getting tougher, and you understand that you cannot live like this.

06:32.000 --> 06:35.000
You understand that you have three options as a distributor.

06:35.000 --> 06:42.000
Either go into production, or go into logistics, become a cool logistics operator, or create your own business.

06:42.000 --> 06:47.000
The second example is also about this.

06:47.000 --> 06:49.000
The company produces lasers.

06:49.000 --> 06:59.000
Until some point, it felt good in the industry, but everything changes, competition changes, suppliers change, clients change.

06:59.000 --> 07:07.000
The management of the company understands that it is impossible to live as we used to live.

07:07.000 --> 07:11.000
I drew three scenarios for myself.

07:11.000 --> 07:19.000
The first scenario is the so-called operational perfection, when the company will bet on a standard mass laser,

07:20.000 --> 07:29.000
to produce lasers in a very narrow range, focusing on the mass market, and polishing its logistics and production.

07:29.000 --> 07:39.000
At the same time, the business cannot boast of innovative ideas, it is unlikely that it can boast of an amazing service or a strong brand.

07:39.000 --> 07:48.000
The second scenario is the product management, which usually involves huge investments in new-ocre, in the final development.

07:48.000 --> 07:57.000
Some of these investments go to waste, but some of them are likely to be successful,

07:57.000 --> 08:02.000
and the company offers the market an absolutely innovative product, an absolutely innovative laser,

08:02.000 --> 08:07.000
and can remove the cream from this product for some time.

08:07.000 --> 08:12.000
The third scenario is customization,

08:12.000 --> 08:19.000
offering a laser to a client with very sharp edges,

08:19.000 --> 08:22.000
because this is what the client wants,

08:22.000 --> 08:29.000
according to Feng Shui, this is correct, when the laser has round corners and yellow color,

08:29.000 --> 08:34.000
as well as a specific lamp that the client wants to see.

08:34.000 --> 08:39.000
There are three ways to go, operational perfection, product management, or int-poshiv.

08:39.000 --> 08:45.000
But the company cannot go in three ways at the same time, due to the limitation of all types of resources.

08:45.000 --> 08:50.000
The third example is the company working on the ice cream market.

08:50.000 --> 08:57.000
In recent years, the ice cream market has not grown very intensively, and at the moment it is not growing at all.

08:58.000 --> 09:06.000
At the same time, another direction has grown, the so-called cold logistics,

09:06.000 --> 09:14.000
that is, cold transport, in which you can transport ice cream, dumplings, frozen vegetables,

09:14.000 --> 09:18.000
and warehouses where all this can also be stored.

09:18.000 --> 09:26.000
This cold logistics has grown to the same volume in terms of revenue and profit as ice cream.

09:26.000 --> 09:34.000
If you do this closely, you can earn a lot, because the market is still quite raw.

09:34.000 --> 09:41.000
And again, the company thinks about how to live further, whether we need this ice cream,

09:41.000 --> 09:47.000
or whether we should become operators in the cold logistics market.

09:47.000 --> 09:52.000
All these three companies, in order to make a conscious strategic choice,

09:52.000 --> 09:57.000
and develop a competitive strategy that is understandable for themselves and for their employees,

09:57.000 --> 10:02.000
must make a so-called strategic analysis at the stage number 0.

10:02.000 --> 10:08.000
The logic of this strategic analysis is presented on this slide.

10:08.000 --> 10:11.000
In a nutshell, it consists of two main tasks,

10:11.000 --> 10:16.000
this is a strategic analysis of the external environment and a strategic analysis of the company itself.

10:16.000 --> 10:22.000
When we analyze the external environment, we usually use two tools.

10:22.000 --> 10:26.000
This is the analysis of the PEST factors, this is the so-called analysis of the remote environment.

10:26.000 --> 10:34.000
The company looks at the policy and legal factors that can influence its work in the near future.

10:34.000 --> 10:39.000
The company tries to understand how the economic environment will behave in which it works.

10:39.000 --> 10:42.000
The company tries to understand the factors of social nature.

10:42.000 --> 10:46.000
And the company tries to understand the factors of technological nature.

10:46.000 --> 10:49.000
But this is the so-called remote environment.

10:49.000 --> 10:53.000
In addition, there are factors of the so-called near environment,

10:53.000 --> 10:57.000
which are very well described in the works of Michael Porter,

10:57.000 --> 11:02.000
and are known as the five-force model.

11:02.000 --> 11:05.000
The first is the competition in the industry,

11:05.000 --> 11:09.000
and the power of the substitutes is the clients and suppliers,

11:09.000 --> 11:14.000
as well as the analysis of the entry barriers that prevent the emergence of new players in the industry.

11:14.000 --> 11:17.000
If we use these two tools,

11:17.000 --> 11:25.000
we will get a good understanding of what is happening and will happen in our external environment.

11:25.000 --> 11:28.000
In addition, in order to develop a strategy,

11:28.000 --> 11:31.000
you need to understand your own strengths and weaknesses,

11:31.000 --> 11:35.000
what is already good and what is not very good.

11:35.000 --> 11:38.000
For these purposes, I recommend the analysis of the strengths and weaknesses,

11:38.000 --> 11:42.000
which can be done in the format of the so-called chain of value creation.

11:42.000 --> 11:47.000
The fourth point is, as a rule, the requirements of the owners,

11:47.000 --> 11:49.000
financial and non-financial,

11:49.000 --> 11:56.000
can significantly affect the strategic choice and the business model

11:56.000 --> 12:00.000
that the employee management is trying to implement in practice.

12:00.000 --> 12:10.000
The results of all these analyses can be summarized in the final summary document,

12:10.000 --> 12:12.000
which is called the SWOT analysis,

12:12.000 --> 12:15.000
and represents a set of strengths and weaknesses,

12:15.000 --> 12:19.000
opportunities and threats listed on a piece of paper in the A4 format,

12:19.000 --> 12:21.000
in the One Page Only format.

12:21.000 --> 12:29.000
After that, we can assess and weigh the further paths of our own development.

12:29.000 --> 12:37.000
We can assess whether we will go into production, logistics, or our own retail,

12:37.000 --> 12:42.000
or we will go into operational improvement, product leadership, or int-poshiv.

12:43.000 --> 12:47.000
After weighing the alternatives, we will make our own strategic choice.

12:52.000 --> 12:55.000
So, the analysis of external environment factors,

12:55.000 --> 12:58.000
which consists of two sections,

12:58.000 --> 13:02.000
the analysis of the factors of the distant environment and the analysis of the factors of the near environment.

13:02.000 --> 13:05.000
When analyzing the factors of the distant environment,

13:05.000 --> 13:08.000
we can use the PEST or STEP model.

13:08.000 --> 13:11.000
I repeat that this is an abbreviation of four English words.

13:11.000 --> 13:14.000
The political-legal environment is the letter P,

13:14.000 --> 13:18.000
the economic environment is the letter E,

13:18.000 --> 13:21.000
the letter S is the factors of the social environment,

13:21.000 --> 13:23.000
and the letter T is technology.

13:23.000 --> 13:29.000
What do we analyze at the stage of the analysis of political-legal issues?

13:29.000 --> 13:34.000
We try to understand how much the law that operates in the external environment

13:34.000 --> 13:39.000
can affect our business.

13:39.000 --> 13:42.000
We try to predict how it will change,

13:42.000 --> 13:46.000
in a positive or negative direction.

13:46.000 --> 13:53.000
The second point is to understand how seriously the state can interfere in our business.

13:53.000 --> 13:59.000
The third point is to understand how great the level of corruption in the market we work in is.

13:59.000 --> 14:04.000
We ask ourselves questions like this

14:05.000 --> 14:07.000
before developing a strategy,

14:07.000 --> 14:10.000
trying to understand our political-legal environment.

14:10.000 --> 14:13.000
A small example on this topic.

14:13.000 --> 14:21.000
Ukraine is a market for buildings made of fast-mounted metal structures.

14:21.000 --> 14:26.000
A construction company offers its customers buildings made of metal.

14:26.000 --> 14:32.000
It can be a logistics center, a warehouse, a production facility,

14:32.000 --> 14:36.000
a hypermarket, a metal box.

14:39.000 --> 14:46.000
In 2005, the company felt very good,

14:46.000 --> 14:50.000
experienced a stage of rapid growth,

14:50.000 --> 14:59.000
at the end of the year it rented a new office space with a margin,

14:59.000 --> 15:04.000
and the sales plan for the next year was quite ambitious.

15:04.000 --> 15:11.000
But due to political reasons, the orange revolution,

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
sales fell significantly next year.

15:15.000 --> 15:19.000
Potential customers did not have less money,

15:19.000 --> 15:24.000
but they were afraid to invest in logistics centers,

15:24.000 --> 15:29.000
hypermarkets, real estate.

15:29.000 --> 15:33.000
They were waiting for the government's decision

15:33.000 --> 15:36.000
on what was allowed and what was not allowed in Ukraine.

15:36.000 --> 15:39.000
They waited for almost a year,

15:39.000 --> 15:41.000
and only in November of the following year,

15:41.000 --> 15:44.000
the company sales began to grow again.

15:44.000 --> 15:54.000
We understand how political factors can affect our success.

15:54.000 --> 15:58.000
The letter E, the letter M, is the economy.

15:58.000 --> 16:03.000
We analyze inflation,

16:03.000 --> 16:07.000
we try to understand how the cost of capital on the market will change,

16:07.000 --> 16:10.000
whether capital will increase or decrease,

16:10.000 --> 16:13.000
we try to understand how unemployment will behave,

16:13.000 --> 16:17.000
what will happen in the labor market, and so on.

16:17.000 --> 16:22.000
The letter S is the social environment factors.

16:22.000 --> 16:27.000
Here we analyze the demography on the market,

16:27.000 --> 16:32.000
we try to understand the cultural features of some markets,

16:32.000 --> 16:36.000
we can analyze the level of education on the market.

16:37.000 --> 16:41.000
These are the questions we discuss,

16:41.000 --> 16:44.000
analyzing the letter S, the social environment.

16:44.000 --> 16:48.000
The fourth section is the technological environment factors.

16:48.000 --> 16:52.000
The influence of the Internet on our business,

16:52.000 --> 16:55.000
the influence of new technologies in our industry,

16:55.000 --> 16:57.000
the influence of IT.

16:57.000 --> 17:03.000
These are the factors we analyze before developing a strategy.

17:04.000 --> 17:06.000
A small nuance.

17:06.000 --> 17:09.000
If a company operates in several markets,

17:09.000 --> 17:12.000
I mean geographical markets,

17:12.000 --> 17:15.000
for example, it operates in the Russian market,

17:15.000 --> 17:17.000
in the Ukrainian market, in the Belarusian market,

17:17.000 --> 17:19.000
and in the Polish market.

17:19.000 --> 17:25.000
It may be that the letter P on these four markets

17:25.000 --> 17:30.000
is quite different and affects the business in a very different way.

17:30.000 --> 17:34.000
Again, the letter E, the economic factors,

17:34.000 --> 17:37.000
can be quite different on these markets

17:37.000 --> 17:39.000
and can also affect our business.

17:39.000 --> 17:44.000
The conclusion is that the company will have to pass this PEST analysis four times.

17:44.000 --> 17:46.000
Pass the PEST analysis for the Russian market,

17:46.000 --> 17:49.000
for the Ukrainian, for the Belarusian, for the Polish,

17:49.000 --> 17:53.000
to understand all the nuances that it will have to consider

17:53.000 --> 17:57.000
in the next two or three years if it wants to continue working on these markets.

17:57.000 --> 17:59.000
A small nuance.

17:59.000 --> 18:01.000
When we do a PEST analysis,

18:01.000 --> 18:06.000
we evaluate the positive or negative impact of all these

18:06.000 --> 18:12.000
political, legal, economic, social and technological factors on our business.

18:12.000 --> 18:15.000
We must understand that the same factors

18:15.000 --> 18:20.000
in companies from different industries can have a positive or negative effect

18:20.000 --> 18:23.000
on some companies, have a neutral effect.

18:23.000 --> 18:27.000
For example, in Krzysztof Obloy's book

18:27.000 --> 18:29.000
The Strategies of a Successful Company,

18:29.000 --> 18:32.000
which is recommended in the list of literature,

18:32.000 --> 18:37.000
there is a funny observation about how the factor on the letter S,

18:37.000 --> 18:42.000
namely the formation of the YAPI class,

18:42.000 --> 18:44.000
Young Professionals,

18:44.000 --> 18:49.000
in Poland, has a very different effect on businesses from different industries.

18:49.000 --> 18:53.000
It is very positive for restaurants,

18:53.000 --> 18:58.000
for car and car salesmen,

18:58.000 --> 19:02.000
that young professionals are being formed in Poland.

19:02.000 --> 19:06.000
But companies that produce children's goods,

19:06.000 --> 19:08.000
diapers, children's food,

19:08.000 --> 19:10.000
they are in complete sorrow,

19:10.000 --> 19:14.000
because YAPI children are usually started late.

19:14.000 --> 19:16.000
And if a company makes tractors,

19:16.000 --> 19:21.000
then the formation of the YAPI group has no effect on it.

19:21.000 --> 19:23.000
And another nuance.

19:23.000 --> 19:25.000
When we do a PEST analysis,

19:25.000 --> 19:29.000
we do not just list the factors that affect us.

19:29.000 --> 19:32.000
We must immediately ask ourselves the question,

19:32.000 --> 19:37.000
what exactly a particular structural unit of our company should do,

19:37.000 --> 19:41.000
or, on the contrary, should not do, in response to the effect of this factor.

19:41.000 --> 19:48.000
In the materials, we have an example of a PEST analysis of a company that produces websites.

19:48.000 --> 19:50.000
It is engaged in web design.

19:50.000 --> 19:58.000
The company is located in one of the regional centers of the Russian Federation.

19:58.000 --> 20:01.000
There it has a production site and a central office.

20:01.000 --> 20:04.000
However, the company is interested in the Moscow market,

20:04.000 --> 20:09.000
and it has a representative here who works with clients

20:10.000 --> 20:13.000
and, analyzing the PEST factors,

20:13.000 --> 20:16.000
the company, for itself, by the letter S,

20:16.000 --> 20:22.000
denotes a high degree of snobbery in public consciousness in Moscow.

20:22.000 --> 20:27.000
And we must immediately understand what this means for our business,

20:27.000 --> 20:30.000
for the individual structural units of our company.

20:30.000 --> 20:35.000
It means that the company should look like a Moscow one,

20:36.000 --> 20:38.000
it should have an office in Moscow,

20:38.000 --> 20:41.000
it should have a convincing client list,

20:41.000 --> 20:44.000
and sometimes for this you have to win a tender

20:44.000 --> 20:49.000
to supply the site, for example, Coca-Cola or Procter & Gamble for 1 euro.

20:49.000 --> 20:52.000
That is, the Coca-Cola company announces a tender,

20:52.000 --> 20:55.000
I want a site,

20:55.000 --> 21:03.000
and the company we are considering won a tender for 1 euro,

21:03.000 --> 21:08.000
because it needs a convincing client list to work in the Moscow market.

21:08.000 --> 21:11.000
So, when we analyze the PEST factors,

21:11.000 --> 21:17.000
we always ask ourselves what this factor means for our company,

21:17.000 --> 21:20.000
how it will affect our company in the near future,

21:20.000 --> 21:25.000
and what we should do and what we should not do in response to this factor.

21:25.000 --> 21:30.000
We have at least two examples from different industries in our materials.

21:31.000 --> 21:34.000
For each tool that we are considering,

21:34.000 --> 21:40.000
the first task that I recommend you to do is to conduct a PEST analysis for your company.

21:40.000 --> 21:49.000
You can find the image of those mini cases, those examples that are in our materials.

21:49.000 --> 21:59.000
PEST analysis of the Russian market with the eyes of the company that makes the sites,

21:59.000 --> 22:05.000
and the example of the PEST analysis of the Ukrainian market with the eyes of the company that works in the kitchen furniture market.

22:05.000 --> 22:11.000
Please remember that if you have to work in several markets,

22:11.000 --> 22:14.000
you will most likely have to do several PEST analyses.

22:14.000 --> 22:18.000
For one market, PEST, and for another market, PEST.

22:18.000 --> 22:24.000
And please remember that you do not just list that inflation is like this,

22:24.000 --> 22:32.000
that the currency rate is like this, that unemployment is like this, and that the level of education is like this.

22:32.000 --> 22:37.000
You must immediately try to understand how this will affect your business in the near future,

22:37.000 --> 22:44.000
and ideally, even form a so-called to-do list, a list of what needs to be done in the near future

22:44.000 --> 22:47.000
in order to take into account the effect of this factor.

22:48.000 --> 23:00.000
For example, the company sells spare parts and says that in recent years there have been more traffic jams on the streets of cities,

23:00.000 --> 23:07.000
and more and more often people began to buy Asian and American brands.

23:07.000 --> 23:09.000
Such trends are on the market.

23:09.000 --> 23:12.000
What does this mean from the point of view of our strategy?

23:12.000 --> 23:20.000
This means that our product portfolio needs to include more spare parts for American and Asian cars.

23:20.000 --> 23:26.000
Given that there are many traffic jams, the clutch breaks, the gearbox breaks,

23:26.000 --> 23:32.000
so the demand for these spare parts will most likely increase, and we will be able to sell more of them in the coming years.

23:32.000 --> 23:37.000
This is a specific conclusion for the product portfolio based on the results of the PEST analysis.

23:37.000 --> 23:44.000
Please, not just a list of factors, but a list of what needs to be done in the next column.

23:44.000 --> 23:49.000
A so-called to-do list, a list of necessary actions,

23:49.000 --> 23:54.000
which can be immediately recorded in a document called a strategy.

24:08.000 --> 24:15.000
The next tool we will look at is the analysis of the factors of the near environment.

