There are nuances of the Ukrainian market, nuances of the Baltic market, nuances of the Russian market.

51:16.000 --> 51:18.000
Let's recall PEST.

51:18.000 --> 51:21.000
Politics, economy, social technology.

51:21.000 --> 51:25.000
All these 4 letters can be distinguished on these 3 markets.

51:25.000 --> 51:28.000
Ukrainian, Baltic and Russian.

51:28.000 --> 51:34.000
The company operates in different cities.

51:34.000 --> 51:40.000
There are no stores yet, but there may be stores in cities with up to 20,000 inhabitants.

51:40.000 --> 51:43.000
Again, there are no stores yet, but this is an interesting segment.

51:43.000 --> 51:46.000
Cities with up to 20-50,000 inhabitants.

51:46.000 --> 51:50.000
Next segment is 50-100,000 inhabitants.

51:50.000 --> 51:53.000
The next segment is 100-1,500.

51:53.000 --> 51:57.000
From 500,000 to a million-city is another segment.

51:57.000 --> 52:01.000
And the last segment is a city with a million-city and above.

52:01.000 --> 52:07.000
The type of occupation of the client is divided into a large number of groups.

52:07.000 --> 52:11.000
We see only 4 groups on this slide.

52:12.000 --> 52:23.000
For example, a student, an office manager of a middle level, an office manager of a high level, a head of a workshop, etc.

52:23.000 --> 52:28.000
The company makes its clients into 3 groups.

52:28.000 --> 52:32.000
Interested, moderate and indifferent.

52:32.000 --> 52:37.000
Let's look at 2 target segments.

52:38.000 --> 52:43.000
Let's try to understand how the company should work with these segments.

52:43.000 --> 52:49.000
The next slide shows a grey segment.

52:49.000 --> 52:53.000
This is a man who earns 2,000 euros.

52:53.000 --> 52:57.000
He is 55 years old.

52:57.000 --> 53:01.000
He is 43 years old.

53:01.000 --> 53:03.000
He lives in Russia.

53:03.000 --> 53:08.000
The population of the city is 750,000.

53:08.000 --> 53:14.000
He works as a head of a workshop in one of the businesses.

53:14.000 --> 53:17.000
He has a rather indifferent attitude to fashion.

53:17.000 --> 53:19.000
This is his portrait.

53:19.000 --> 53:22.000
This is a portrait of a second client.

53:22.000 --> 53:27.000
This is a woman who earns 620 euros per month.

53:27.000 --> 53:30.000
She is 24 years old.

53:30.000 --> 53:32.000
She is 37 years old.

53:32.000 --> 53:36.000
She lives in Ukraine, in a million-city, Kiev.

53:36.000 --> 53:39.000
She works as an office manager of a middle level.

53:39.000 --> 53:42.000
She has an attitude to fashion.

53:42.000 --> 53:45.000
These are 2 very different clients.

53:45.000 --> 53:50.000
If a company wants to work with grey and yellow,

53:50.000 --> 53:55.000
it should understand the portrait of each client.

53:55.000 --> 53:57.000
It is very simple.

53:57.000 --> 54:02.000
The better we understand our client, the more we earn.

54:02.000 --> 54:09.000
If we can draw a portrait of our grey client in the smallest details,

54:10.000 --> 54:15.000
there is a high probability that we will earn a lot.

54:15.000 --> 54:22.000
If a company is oriented to the yellow and grey segments,

54:22.000 --> 54:25.000
its entire chain of processes,

54:25.000 --> 54:28.000
from the design, to the purchase, to the production,

54:28.000 --> 54:31.000
to the branding, to the distribution, to the retail,

54:31.000 --> 54:34.000
can be very different.

54:34.000 --> 54:39.000
One chain of processes will be focused on the yellow segment,

54:39.000 --> 54:43.000
and the other chain of processes will be focused on the grey segment.

54:43.000 --> 54:46.000
We should understand this very well.

54:46.000 --> 54:48.000
When we analyze our clients,

54:48.000 --> 54:52.000
the list of questions can be as follows.

54:52.000 --> 54:54.000
First of all, as we have already said,

54:54.000 --> 55:00.000
we try to assess the profitability of our target segments.

55:00.000 --> 55:03.000
How much the yellow or grey segments,

55:03.000 --> 55:07.000
or any other segment that interests us,

55:07.000 --> 55:10.000
can trade with us in terms of price and payment conditions,

55:10.000 --> 55:14.000
and how it will be able to change in the near future.

55:14.000 --> 55:17.000
What is our current situation, and what will it be in 2-3 years?

55:17.000 --> 55:20.000
The second question is the volume of purchases.

55:20.000 --> 55:25.000
How much and how often does one segment buy,

55:25.000 --> 55:28.000
and how much and how often does the other segment buy?

55:28.000 --> 55:34.000
It may be that your business has a segment that buys a little bit, but often,

55:34.000 --> 55:40.000
or maybe you have a segment that buys a lot, but very rarely.

55:40.000 --> 55:43.000
The client's portrait changes.

55:43.000 --> 55:46.000
It is one now, tomorrow it will be another.

55:46.000 --> 55:49.000
We should understand how the needs of the target segments,

55:49.000 --> 55:53.000
which we are focused on in our business, will change in the near future.

55:53.000 --> 55:59.000
The next factor, which can be very important in some industries,

55:59.000 --> 56:02.000
is the cost of switching from one provider to another,

56:02.000 --> 56:04.000
and the level of loyalty.

56:04.000 --> 56:06.000
What do I mean by this?

56:06.000 --> 56:09.000
If we are talking about household chemicals,

56:09.000 --> 56:11.000
for example, washing powder,

56:11.000 --> 56:16.000
then in this industry the cost of switching from one player to another is usually not very high.

56:16.000 --> 56:19.000
Today I am using one washing powder,

56:19.000 --> 56:22.000
tomorrow I will not like it, I will switch it to another,

56:22.000 --> 56:24.000
and it is not difficult for me.

56:24.000 --> 56:27.000
However, if we are talking about software for business,

56:27.000 --> 56:29.000
some IT solution,

56:29.000 --> 56:34.000
then switching from one provider to another is like a marriage-divorce process.

56:34.000 --> 56:38.000
It is quite difficult, painful and expensive.

56:38.000 --> 56:43.000
If the costs of switching from one provider to another are high,

56:43.000 --> 56:46.000
then the client's power will be higher.

56:46.000 --> 56:49.000
Another factor that we can analyze,

56:50.000 --> 56:55.000
is the share of costs of buying the product we offer in the cost structure.

56:55.000 --> 57:00.000
For example, if we offer the end product to the client,

57:00.000 --> 57:03.000
and the client is a metallurgical plant,

57:03.000 --> 57:10.000
then the share of costs of buying the product will be low,

57:10.000 --> 57:15.000
and the price sensitivity will be low.

57:15.000 --> 57:22.000
If we offer the end product to a metallurgical plant at a high price,

57:22.000 --> 57:26.000
the client will not feel it,

57:26.000 --> 57:33.000
because the share of the total purchases in the structure is negligible.

57:33.000 --> 57:38.000
Another point that we should analyze,

57:38.000 --> 57:44.000
is the possibility of integration forward or backward along the chain.

57:44.000 --> 57:46.000
What do I mean?

57:46.000 --> 57:50.000
Let's imagine an oil refinery,

57:50.000 --> 57:54.000
which can rewind the chain of its processes.

57:54.000 --> 57:56.000
What does it mean?

57:56.000 --> 58:03.000
It means that it can try to put drilling towers in the oil production area,

58:03.000 --> 58:07.000
or extend the chain forward,

58:07.000 --> 58:14.000
or make its own network of gas stations.

58:14.000 --> 58:18.000
If we have the opportunity to extend the chain forward,

58:18.000 --> 58:21.000
we are an oil refinery,

58:21.000 --> 58:24.000
and we can easily put our own gas stations,

58:24.000 --> 58:29.000
then our position in negotiations on the price of the gas network is stronger.

58:29.000 --> 58:32.000
Another factor is the seasonality.

58:32.000 --> 58:34.000
So, the conclusion is as follows.

58:34.000 --> 58:43.000
We segment our clients in order to understand the needs and behavior of each of the segments that interest us,

58:43.000 --> 58:46.000
and to work with each of them in different ways.

58:46.000 --> 58:52.000
It is obvious that the work of a company with a target segment of a woman of pre-retirement age,

58:52.000 --> 58:57.000
who works as a chief accountant of a large machine-building enterprise,

58:57.000 --> 59:03.000
and who values agility and comfort in shoes,

59:03.000 --> 59:08.000
should work with one method, and with another target segment.

59:08.000 --> 59:12.000
A young woman of 25 years,

59:12.000 --> 59:17.000
who prefers brightness, style and uniqueness in shoes,

59:17.000 --> 59:20.000
with this target segment of the company,

59:20.000 --> 59:23.000
in all parts of the chain of its own processes,

59:23.000 --> 59:25.000
should work differently.

59:25.000 --> 59:32.000
It is very important to understand how the portrait of your client will change in the near future,

59:32.000 --> 59:42.000
and to be prepared for the fact that the chain of processes will have to be redone and sharpened to meet the needs of each segment.

59:42.000 --> 59:46.000
The second example on the same topic is from another industry,

59:46.000 --> 59:49.000
the production of kitchen furniture.

59:49.000 --> 59:52.000
The company that we have already talked about,

59:52.000 --> 59:57.000
divides its clients into four segments in terms of payment capabilities,

59:57.000 --> 01:00:04.000
highlighting low incomes, medium, medium-high and high,

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:08.000
as well as into four parts in terms of proven values.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:14.000
The example of this matrix, the example of segmentation of clients,

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:19.000
is described in detail in this business in your materials.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:22.000
Having discussed our clients,

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:25.000
and analyzed the target segments,

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:30.000
and chosen the most interesting for ourselves,

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:37.000
we should think about how to take these chests with money at the lowest possible costs for resources.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:40.000
In this case, we need to analyze the suppliers.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:46.000
It is very useful to imagine the reports of profits and losses,

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:50.000
in which on the one hand there are incomes, and on the other there are expenses.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:55.000
When we analyze the clients, we try to find those interesting segments

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:58.000
from which we could take more money,

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:02.000
and sharpen our chain of processes accordingly.

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:06.000
When we analyze our suppliers, we are talking about our expenses.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Here we should analyze all the articles of our costs.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:17.000
It can be raw materials, it can be electricity, it can be equipment suppliers,

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:24.000
it can be suppliers of square meters of heating and lighting,

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:29.000
it can be suppliers of all kinds of services, transport, information, insurance, and so on.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:33.000
It can be channels of communication with clients.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:39.000
If we decide that advertising time on TV is very expensive,

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:42.000
we can try to reach out to the client via the Internet,

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:47.000
or through external advertising, or some other means.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:55.000
A very important supplier is the staff that supplies us with their heads and hands,

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:00.000
which we use in our business and for which we pay some money.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:04.000
And, of course, a very important supplier is the supplier of capital.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:11.000
It can be banks, it can be other structures that can give us money for development,

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:16.000
and the money is not free, it costs a certain percentage.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:20.000
One way or another, we have to go through the entire list of our expenses,

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:27.000
evaluating the ability of suppliers to trade with us at the price and on the terms of payment.

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:32.000
The main questions when analyzing suppliers are as follows.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:37.000
First of all, again, it is the ability to trade at the price and on the terms of payment.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:40.000
The second question is readiness for the stability of deliveries,

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:44.000
both the quality parameters and the time parameters.

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:52.000
Is the supplier we work with able to provide us with the level of quality we would like to have

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:58.000
and to supply our product or service that is stated in the contract?

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:05.000
The third question we can ask ourselves is whether there are substitutes for the product that the supplier supplies us with.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:12.000
If there are, then the position of the supplier in negotiations changes, the power of the supplier decreases.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:18.000
The same thing happens if we have an alternative for each type of resource,

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:23.000
if we can turn to a large enough list of suppliers.

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:27.000
For example, if we open the yellow page of the reference book,

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:34.000
and for each type of resource we need in our industry there are 384 tomato suppliers,

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:37.000
and all the tomato suppliers have the same number of suppliers,

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:41.000
then the power of the tomato suppliers over us will be small.

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:47.000
In some industries, a fairly important factor may be the distance of the suppliers,

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:51.000
as well as the ability to integrate back and forth.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:57.000
If our supplier can easily extend the chain forward,

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:03.000
become our direct competitor, then his position in negotiations is stronger.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:09.000
And vice versa, if we can easily unwind the chain and tell the supplier

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:13.000
that we are able to make the parts that you supply us,

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:16.000
then it is very easy for us.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:21.000
Accordingly, our position in negotiations becomes stronger.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:27.000
The second task that I recommend you to do is to analyze the factors of the environment,

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:33.000
try to understand your industry through the FiveForce model, the five forces of Michael Porter.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:38.000
Everyone has competition, everyone has clients and suppliers,

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:40.000
and there are entry barriers in any industry.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:45.000
Is there a substitute product factor in your business?

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:49.000
I don't know, because there are companies for which there is no problem with a substitute product,

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:53.000
but there are industries where there are a lot of substitute products from other industries.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:05:00.000
There is a point of view that Porter did not take into account all the factors in the industry within his FiveForce concept.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:05.000
For example, some experts suggest adding the sixth force of the state,

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:10.000
but in principle, the state factor can be spread over all the five forces,

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:14.000
because the state can be a competitor, a supplier, a client,

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:23.000
an entry barrier, like a writer of some regulatory acts or a customs officer.

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:27.000
But in principle, we discussed the state factor when we were submitting the PEST analysis.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:32.000
The letter P, the letter P, the legal issues, we discussed them.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:38.000
But it seems to me that everything is quite consistent and logical in the FiveForce concept.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:44.000
Please remember that you are not just listing factors,

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:51.000
you are again, as with the PEST analysis, trying to understand what this means for your business,

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:54.000
what is included in the list of actions, what is included in the to-do list.

01:05:55.000 --> 01:06:04.000
If the client's demand increases and the clients will be divided into more or less homogeneous groups,

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:09.000
each of which will have its own specific needs, requests, and so on,

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:14.000
then you will most likely need to develop a certain service model for each target group,

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:22.000
develop a standard, train the staff and control the implementation of this standard.

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:27.000
This is a fairly specific action that we record in our strategy, analyzing our clients.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:31.000
And please remember that if your business operates at the junction of industries,

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:37.000
IT, marketing, business education, the recreation industry,

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:44.000
you will have to do this work twice, do the analysis of the FiveForce for both industries,

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:51.000
to take into account all the factors that you need to track when developing your strategy.
